<!-- ── SECTION 1: EXECUTIVE SUMMARY ────────────────────────── -->
<section class="wp-section" id="executive-summary">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-eyebrow">Section 01</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Executive Summary</h2>
  </div>

  <p>Governments and critical infrastructure operators around the world are confronting an unprecedented challenge: as they digitise public services, the very systems upon which citizens and economies depend are increasingly owned, operated, and governed by foreign entities beyond national regulatory reach. Data is processed across jurisdictions. Cloud platforms concentrate infrastructure in the hands of a small number of non-domestic hyperscalers. Artificial intelligence systems trained on foreign data and governed by foreign law make consequential decisions affecting millions of citizens. Meanwhile, the legal frameworks required to govern this landscape often lag a decade or more behind technological reality.</p>

  <p>The <strong>Digital &amp; Data Sovereignty Assessment Tool (DDSAT)</strong> was developed in response to this challenge. It provides governments, regulatory authorities, and critical infrastructure operators with a rigorous, structured methodology to evaluate their current sovereignty posture, identify gaps, and generate a quantitative baseline for strategic planning and remediation. DDSAT is not a compliance checklist — it is a maturity assessment framework that measures where an organisation sits on a five-level scale from <em>Initial / Ad-hoc</em> to <em>Optimizing</em>, across the full breadth of what it means to exercise genuine digital sovereignty in the modern era.</p>

  <p>The tool is organised around <strong>five strategic pillars</strong>, each addressing a distinct dimension of sovereignty: Legal &amp; Regulatory Alignment; Data Localization &amp; Infrastructure; Critical Infrastructure Protection; Cross-Border Data Flow Governance; and Institutional Capacity &amp; Oversight. Across these pillars, DDSAT assesses <strong>14 domains</strong> through <strong>84 structured questions</strong>, producing domain-level scores, pillar scores, and an aggregate <strong>Digital Sovereignty Index (DSI)</strong> — a single, quantifiable measure of an organisation's overall sovereign posture on a 0–100 scale.</p>

  <p>From this assessment, DDSAT generates <strong>12 Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)</strong> that translate technical findings into executive-level metrics suitable for board reporting, ministerial briefings, and inter-agency benchmarking. Prioritised recommendations — ranked by severity and strategic impact — provide a clear remediation pathway aligned to the organisation's maturity level and resource constraints.</p>

  <p>Three core strategic outcomes anchor DDSAT's design. First, <strong>protecting citizen data</strong>: ensuring that personal data collected by government is handled lawfully, stored within appropriate jurisdictions, and protected from unlawful foreign access. Second, <strong>controlling and governing digital infrastructure</strong>: ensuring that the systems upon which public services depend remain under national authority and cannot be disrupted, disabled, or exploited by foreign actors. Third, <strong>ensuring continuity of service delivery</strong>: guaranteeing that governments can maintain essential services for citizens even in the face of cyberattacks, geopolitical disruption, or the withdrawal of foreign technology providers.</p>

  <p>Digital sovereignty is not an end state — it is an ongoing practice of governance. DDSAT provides the baseline measurement, the strategic language, and the executive visibility that governments need to make sovereignty a sustained organisational priority rather than a reactive afterthought.</p>
</section>

