<!-- ── SECTION 3: DDSAT CONCEPTUAL FRAMEWORK ─────────────── -->
<section class="wp-section" id="framework">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-eyebrow">Section 03</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">DDSAT Conceptual Framework</h2>
  </div>

  <div class="subsection">
    <h3 class="subsection-title">3.1 &nbsp;Purpose and Scope</h3>
    <p>DDSAT is designed to provide organisations with a systematic, evidence-based method for evaluating their current digital sovereignty posture. Unlike compliance frameworks that assess adherence to a fixed set of rules, DDSAT measures capability maturity — enabling organisations to understand not just whether they have a policy in place, but whether that policy is effectively implemented, monitored, tested, and continuously improved.</p>
    <p>The tool is designed for use by three primary audience groups: <strong>national governments and central government departments</strong> seeking to understand and improve their whole-of-government sovereignty posture; <strong>regulatory authorities</strong> wishing to assess the sovereignty dimensions of regulated sectors; and <strong>critical infrastructure operators</strong> — including organisations in energy, water, telecommunications, finance, transport, and health — who must ensure that the systems underpinning essential services remain under appropriate national control.</p>
    <p>DDSAT is scoped to cover the breadth of digital sovereignty: it is not solely a cybersecurity assessment, nor a data protection compliance audit, nor a cloud strategy review — though it encompasses all three. Its distinctive value lies in integrating these dimensions into a single, coherent sovereignty framework that produces a unified index and enables cross-domain prioritisation.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subsection">
    <h3 class="subsection-title">3.2 &nbsp;Design Principles</h3>
  </div>

  <div class="principles-grid">
    <div class="principle-card"><div class="principle-icon">🌐</div><div class="principle-title">Comprehensive Coverage</div><div class="principle-desc">Addresses all material dimensions of digital sovereignty from legal through to AI, across 14 domains and 84 questions.</div></div>
    <div class="principle-card"><div class="principle-icon">📈</div><div class="principle-title">Maturity-Based</div><div class="principle-desc">Measures capability on a five-level scale rather than binary pass/fail, enabling nuanced gap identification and improvement tracking.</div></div>
    <div class="principle-card"><div class="principle-icon">🎯</div><div class="principle-title">Actionable Outputs</div><div class="principle-desc">Every assessment produces prioritised recommendations, domain scores, and a DSI suitable for executive reporting and board-level decision-making.</div></div>
    <div class="principle-card"><div class="principle-icon">📊</div><div class="principle-title">Quantifiable KPIs</div><div class="principle-desc">Generates 12 KPIs that translate assessment findings into measurable, trackable metrics aligned to strategic and operational goals.</div></div>
    <div class="principle-card"><div class="principle-icon">🔓</div><div class="principle-title">Vendor-Neutral</div><div class="principle-desc">Assessment criteria are technology and vendor agnostic, focusing on sovereignty outcomes rather than specific product choices.</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="subsection">
    <h3 class="subsection-title">3.3 &nbsp;Relationship to International Standards</h3>
    <p>DDSAT does not seek to replace existing international standards and frameworks — rather, it complements and integrates them within a sovereignty-specific lens. Organisations that have implemented controls aligned to <strong>ISO/IEC 27001</strong> (information security management) will find their investments reflected in DDSAT's encryption, IAM, and vendor management domains. Those operating under <strong>NIST CSF 2.0</strong> will find natural alignment with DDSAT's critical infrastructure and operational sovereignty domains.</p>
    <p>The <strong>EU NIS2 Directive</strong> (2022) and its national transpositions introduce mandatory cybersecurity and incident reporting requirements for essential entities across critical sectors; DDSAT's critical infrastructure and operational sovereignty pillars directly assess compliance-relevant capabilities. The <strong>GDPR</strong> and equivalent national data protection laws underpin DDSAT's legal alignment and data protection domains. Finally, <strong>ENISA's Cloud Computing Risk Assessment</strong> and the EU's evolving AI Act inform DDSAT's cloud sovereignty and AI governance domains respectively.</p>
    <p>Where an organisation already holds relevant certifications or has undergone recent external audits, DDSAT assessors should use those findings as evidential inputs to the scoring process, avoiding duplication of effort while ensuring the sovereignty-specific dimensions that those frameworks do not address are fully evaluated.</p>
  </div>
</section>

