<!-- ── SECTION 5: THE 14 ASSESSMENT DOMAINS ──────────────── -->
<section class="wp-section" id="domains">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-eyebrow">Section 05</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">The 14 Assessment Domains</h2>
  </div>
  <p>Each pillar is subdivided into domains — the discrete areas of sovereignty that the assessment evaluates through targeted questions. The 14 domains are listed below, grouped by pillar, with a summary of each domain's scope.</p>

  <div class="domains-grid">
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">⚖️</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt1">Pillar 1</span><div class="domain-name">Legal &amp; Regulatory Framework</div><div class="domain-desc-card">National data protection law, DPA independence and enforcement capacity, legal bases for data processing, data localisation mandates, and AI governance legislation.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">🔐</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt1">Pillar 1</span><div class="domain-name">Data Protection Compliance</div><div class="domain-desc-card">DPO designation, DPIA implementation, privacy-by-design, breach notification procedures, and consent management mechanisms.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">🗄️</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt2">Pillar 2</span><div class="domain-name">Data Residency &amp; Storage</div><div class="domain-desc-card">Data inventory completeness, percentage of data stored nationally, technical and contractual residency controls, classification schemes, and DR/backup sovereignty.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">🖥️</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt2">Pillar 2</span><div class="domain-name">Infrastructure Control</div><div class="domain-desc-card">National ownership of critical IT assets, infrastructure sovereignty strategy, technology stack visibility, supply chain security, and operational independence from foreign vendors.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">☁️</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt2">Pillar 2</span><div class="domain-name">Cloud &amp; Infrastructure Sovereignty</div><div class="domain-desc-card">Sovereign cloud strategy, workload placement, contract sovereignty provisions, exit strategy maturity, jurisdictional compliance, and log retention governance.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">🔑</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt2">Pillar 2</span><div class="domain-name">Encryption &amp; Key Sovereignty</div><div class="domain-desc-card">Key ownership and national control, key management policy, HSM deployment, approved cryptographic standards, and key lifecycle governance including rotation and emergency recovery.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">🏗️</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt3">Pillar 3</span><div class="domain-name">Critical Infrastructure Protection</div><div class="domain-desc-card">CNI register completeness, CIP programme maturity, cyber-physical dependency mapping, CSIRT/SOC capability, IR plan testing, and foreign investment screening.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">🔗</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt3">Pillar 3</span><div class="domain-name">Vendor &amp; Supply Chain Management</div><div class="domain-desc-card">Vendor risk assessment processes, sovereignty contract clauses, prohibited vendor lists, concentration risk management, supply chain verification, and MSP requirements.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">🌐</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt4">Pillar 4</span><div class="domain-name">Cross-Border Data Flow Governance</div><div class="domain-desc-card">Transfer policies and enforcement, Transfer Impact Assessments, SCCs and equivalent mechanisms, transfer registers, technical flow controls, and international framework engagement.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">🔍</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt4">Pillar 4</span><div class="domain-name">Vendor Access Audit</div><div class="domain-desc-card">Comprehensive vendor access logging, access recertification schedules, JIT privileged access controls, jurisdictional access restrictions, supervisory requirements, and immutable audit trails.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">🪪</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt5">Pillar 5</span><div class="domain-name">Identity &amp; Access Management</div><div class="domain-desc-card">Enterprise IAM framework, universal MFA enforcement, PAM deployment, automated provisioning/deprovisioning, zero-trust architecture, national PKI adoption, and least-privilege reviews.</div></div></div>
    <div class="domain-card"><div class="domain-icon">🤖</div><div class="domain-info"><span class="domain-pillar-tag pt5">Pillar 5</span><div class="domain-name">AI Governance &amp; Sovereignty</div><div class="domain-desc-card">AI system inventory, governance framework enforcement, training data provenance and residency, AI sovereignty risk assessment, human oversight requirements, national AI strategy, and data exfiltration controls.</div></div></div>
