<!-- ── SECTION 6: SCORING METHODOLOGY & MATURITY MODEL ───── -->
<section class="wp-section" id="scoring">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-eyebrow">Section 06</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Scoring Methodology &amp; Maturity Model</h2>
  </div>

  <div class="subsection">
    <h3 class="subsection-title">6.1 &nbsp;Question Design</h3>
    <p>DDSAT comprises <strong>84 questions</strong> distributed across the 14 domains. Each question presents four response options arranged on an ascending maturity scale. The four levels — <em>Critical</em> (scored 0), <em>Developing</em> (scored 1), <em>Managed</em> (scored 2), and <em>Optimizing</em> (scored 3) — are carefully calibrated to reflect meaningfully distinct capability states. Response options are phrased as concrete, observable characteristics rather than abstract aspirations, enabling assessors to select the option that most accurately describes current organisational practice rather than intended future state.</p>
    <p>Questions are structured to distinguish between the existence of a policy and its effective implementation; between documentation and active enforcement; between capability and tested, demonstrated practice. This design prevents organisations from over-claiming maturity on the basis of written policies that have not been operationalised — a common failure mode in maturity assessments that use broader, more subjective response scales.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subsection">
    <h3 class="subsection-title">6.2 &nbsp;Domain Scoring</h3>
    <p>Each domain score is calculated as the sum of all question scores within that domain, expressed as a percentage of the maximum possible score for that domain. Where a domain contains questions of varying strategic importance, responses are averaged to produce a domain percentage score on a 0–100 scale.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subsection">
    <h3 class="subsection-title">6.3 &nbsp;Pillar Scoring</h3>
    <p>Each pillar score is the simple arithmetic mean of the domain scores within that pillar, also expressed on a 0–100 scale. This approach ensures that all domains within a pillar contribute equally to the pillar score, preventing a single high-scoring domain from masking critical gaps in adjacent domains.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subsection">
    <h3 class="subsection-title">6.4 &nbsp;Digital Sovereignty Index (DSI)</h3>
    <p>The DSI is the weighted composite of all five pillar scores, with weights reflecting each pillar's relative strategic importance to overall sovereignty. The weights are fixed at: P1 Legal &amp; Regulatory = 20%; P2 Data Localization &amp; Infrastructure = 25%; P3 Critical Infrastructure = 20%; P4 Cross-Border Governance = 15%; P5 Institutional Capacity = 20%.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula-label">Scoring Formulae</div>
    <div class="formula-line"><strong>Domain Score</strong> &nbsp;= &nbsp;( Σ Question Scores ) ÷ ( n × 3 ) &nbsp;× &nbsp;100</div>
    <div class="formula-line"><strong>Pillar Score</strong> &nbsp;= &nbsp;( Σ Domain Scores within Pillar ) ÷ ( Number of Domains in Pillar )</div>
    <div class="formula-line"><strong>DSI</strong> &nbsp;= &nbsp;( P1 × 0.20 ) + ( P2 × 0.25 ) + ( P3 × 0.20 ) + ( P4 × 0.15 ) + ( P5 × 0.20 )</div>
    <div class="formula-note">Where n = number of questions in the domain; each question scored 0 (Critical), 1 (Developing), 2 (Managed), or 3 (Optimizing). All scores expressed on a 0–100 scale.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="subsection">
    <h3 class="subsection-title">6.5 &nbsp;Five Maturity Levels</h3>
    <p>DDSAT maps DSI and domain scores to five maturity levels, each with a distinct organisational profile and remediation posture. The maturity scale is designed to provide meaningful differentiation at all score ranges, avoiding the compression of real capability differences that characterises binary pass/fail assessments.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="maturity-container">
    <div class="maturity-bar">
      <div class="mat-seg mat-initial">Initial</div>
      <div class="mat-seg mat-developing">Developing</div>
      <div class="mat-seg mat-defined">Defined</div>
      <div class="mat-seg mat-managed">Managed</div>
      <div class="mat-seg mat-optimizing">Optimizing</div>
    </div>
    <div class="maturity-labels">
